Tony Blair said that he would use the opportunity to return as a British prime minister, but acknowledges that a comeback is unlikely.
In an interview this evening on the occasion of the fifth anniversary of his leaving office, the 59-year-old announced his views on various domestic issues.
Since his resignation in June 2007 after a decade as leader, Blair has largely avoided to comment on British politics, and his comments on to the foreign policy and its role as an envoy of the Quartet of peacemakers in the Middle East.
On the question of whether he would like to return to the post of prime minister, Blair was quoted by the Evening Standard in London with the words: "Yes, sure, but it is unlikely that this happens, so..."
